Hannah was a quiet librarian who had zero desire for attention. After a stressful week, she decided to unwind by visiting a quirky gift shop. There, she bought a giant, neon-orange tote bag‚Äîofficial merchandise from a random indie film. She didn't even like the movie; she just needed a bag.

The next day, she carried the merch to a local cafe. Instantly, a nosy stranger approached. "Oh! I love your bag! That color really suits you!" Hannah wanted to say, "I‚Äôm glad you noticed," but she just nodded awkwardly. The stranger didn't stop. "That's from the movie set in the Atlantic, right? I love how you interpret the meaning of that film through your fashion!"

Hannah‚Äôs appetite for her croissant disappeared. She just wanted to read in peace, but the bag was a beacon. Later, she saw two friends arguing nearby. When they saw her bag, they stopped. "Is that the 'Peace Bag' from the movie?" one asked. Looking at the bright orange bag, they seemed to resolve their differences immediately and made up right there in the cafe, all thanks to her "inspiring" style.

Exasperated by the constant interruptions, Hannah went to the park and left the bag on a bench. "Someone else can have the spotlight," she muttered. She walked away, feeling lighter.

Suddenly, a jogger caught up to her. "Excuse me! You dropped your... oh, wait. I just had to say, you look great in that simple white tee! You have a great sense of style. Not everyone can pull off such a minimalist look, but you do!"

Hannah realized it didn't matter what she carried. She was just the kind of person who made everyone want to start a conversation.
